  <div class="ct">
  
<p>So what's the premise behind the NYT argument against the escalation of money in politics through the morphing of OFA. &nbsp;Its seems to be that the progressive left can't escalate money in politics through organizations like OFA and still be for getting money out of politics. &nbsp;So what would they like us to do, not spend money on our candidates and causes out of some blind adherence to principle, while the other side ravages the political system with out of control spending on their candidates and causes? &nbsp;</p>
<p>That's both naive and insane. &nbsp;While the system exists, we must play in it or we will lose. &nbsp;That doesn't mean we have to abandon are fight for things like a Constitutional Amendment to clarify that corporations are not people in order to be seen as not compromising our principles. &nbsp;In fact, ironically, if we ever hope to win Constitutional changes such as this, we are going to have to pour money into the political system to elect representatives who will support these changes.</p>
<p>NYT should get off its high horse and look at the reality of the current situation.</p>

  </div>
