    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Of course, I agree with the gist of Tom Diaz's article, namely that there should be more gun control and that we should spend more money on research into gun violence and less on anti-terrorism. &nbsp;That said, there's an either/or argument being made here that, like most either/or arguments, bothers me. &nbsp;I don't see any reason why people can't be concerned (and government money can't be spent) on <strong>both</strong> terrorism from external enemies and the very-serious problem of domestic gun violence. &nbsp;In fact, as the Brady Campaign has been arguing for many years, the two issues go hand-in-hand; weak U.S. gun laws help make it easier for al-Qaeda and their associates to get weapons, which they can then use for terrorism. &nbsp;</p>
<p>Also, it bothers me how often I see liberals dismiss concerns about terrorism by arguing that it takes fewer lives than other threats, or is "very rare" (to use the words the diary uses). &nbsp;Government is rightly concerned about both dangers that take many lives, and others that take fewer lives; relatively few people die from drowning or defective consumer products, yet we (rightly) have swimming advisory warnings and a Consumer Product Safety Commission. &nbsp;Moreover, terrorism does damage to a society far beyond the number of lives immediately affected by it, and there is broad agreement all over the political spectrum that protecting the U.S. from outside threats is a prime responsibility of the federal government. &nbsp;</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig">
"Optimism is better than despair." --Jack Layton, the late Canadian MP, liberal, and Christian.
</p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:31856">lungfish</a> on <a href="/comments/1191181/49530221#c41">Sun Mar 03, 2013 at 07:27:13 AM PST</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	





